This section of code joins the various datasets of interest to create the joined data. It then filters based on the relevant requirements.

weightdrug_data <- right_join(hb_data, year_data, by = join_by(hb == hbt)) %>% 
  filter(str_detect(bnf_item_description, "GLUTIDE|OZEMPIC|SAXENDA|TRULICITY")) %>% 
  group_by(hb_name, hb, bnf_item_description) %>% 
  summarise(paid_quantity = sum(paid_quantity))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'hb_name', 'hb'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
joined_data <- left_join(weightdrug_data, population_data) %>%
  left_join(., NHS_healthboards, by = join_by(hb == HBCode))
## Joining with `by = join_by(hb_name)`
joined_data <- left_join(joined_data, deprivation_data, by = join_by(hb == hb))

This section of code generates a graph.

First graph shows the comparison between SIMD and prescriptions of weigh loss drugs.

The second and third graph show the distribution of these prescriptions around Scotland.

I would like to explore the relationship between BMI and deprivaton and how that affects prescription of weight loss drugs.

joined_data %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = paid_quantity, y = simd2020v2country_decile)) +
  geom_smooth() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text( 
    angle = 90,
    size=7, 
    face=3)) +
  labs(title = "Prescriptions vs SIMD", x = "Prescriptions", y = "SIMD")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

weightdrug_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = paid_quantity, x = reorder(hb_name, paid_quantity))) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "No. of weight loss drug prescriptions per health board", x = "Health Board Name", y = "Weight Loss Drugs Prescriptions per person")

joined_data %>% 
ggplot(aes(geometry = geometry, fill = paid_quantity)) +
  geom_sf() +
  scale_fill_distiller(palette = "GnBu") +
  labs(title = "Number of Weight Loss Drug Prescriptions", subtitle = "In Scotland", fill = "Total No. of Prescriptions") +  
  annotation_scale(location = "tl") +
  annotation_north_arrow(
    location = "tl",    
    pad_y = unit(0.5, "in"),    
    style = north_arrow_nautical(
      fill = c("blue", "white"),      
      line_col = "grey20"
    ) 
  )
